('newt','A small, semi-aquatic amphibian with bright colors','LC','Chordata','Vertebrata','Amphibia','Caudata','Salamandridae','2023-10-28 21:47:56.863','2023-11-12 00:13:28.512',58,NULL,'https://images.pexels.com/photos/17231250/pexels-photo-17231250/free-photo-of-photo-of-a-red-salamander-on-a-wet-ground-with-gravel.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1600'),
('eagle','A powerful and majestic bird of prey','LC','Chordata','Vertebrata','Aves','Accipitriformes','Accipitridae','2023-10-28 21:47:56.863','2023-11-12 22:14:34.634',50,'<p class="has-line-data" data-line-start="0" data-line-end="1">Eagles, with their majestic presence and powerful flight, have fascinated humans for centuries. These large birds of prey, belonging to the family Accipitridae, are known for their keen eyesight, strong talons, and regal bearing. Their remarkable abilities and distinctive appearance have made them symbols of power, freedom, and transcendence in various cultures across the globe.</p> <h2 class="code-line" data-line-start=2 data-line-end=3 ><a id="History_2"></a>History</h2> <p class="has-line-data" data-line-start="3" data-line-end="4">The history of eagles intertwines with human civilizations. Ancient cultures, including the Greeks and Romans, revered eagles as sacred animals. In Greek mythology, the eagle was associated with Zeus, the king of gods, symbolizing strength and authority. The Roman legions also used the eagle as their standard, epitomizing imperial power and unity.</p> <h2 class="code-line" data-line-start=5 data-line-end=6 ><a id="Impact_5"></a>Impact</h2> <p class="has-line-data" data-line-start="6" data-line-end="7">Eagles have had a significant impact both ecologically and culturally. As apex predators, they play a crucial role in their ecosystems, controlling populations of smaller animals and maintaining ecological balance. Culturally, they have been a source of inspiration in art, literature, and national symbols. The bald eagle, for instance, is a prominent emblem of the United States, representing freedom and national pride.</p> <h2 class="code-line" data-line-start=8 data-line-end=9 ><a id="Locations_8"></a>Locations</h2> <p class="has-line-data" data-line-start="9" data-line-end="10">Eagles are found worldwide, with their habitats ranging from the Arctic tundras to tropical rainforests. The Bald Eagle is primarily found in North America, while the Golden Eagle is more widespread, inhabiting regions of North America, Europe, Asia, and North Africa. Other notable species include the Harpy Eagle in the rainforests of Central and South America and the Philippine Eagle in the Philippines.</p> <h2 class="code-line" data-line-start=11 data-line-end=12 ><a id="Daily_Routine_and_Habits_11"></a>Daily Routine and Habits</h2> <p class="has-line-data" data-line-start="12" data-line-end="13">Eagles are diurnal birds, active during the day. They usually start their day at sunrise, scouting from high perches or soaring in the sky to locate prey. Their diet mainly consists of fish, small mammals, and other birds. Eagles are known for their incredible hunting skills, often diving at high speeds to catch their prey unawares.</p> <h2 class="code-line" data-line-start=14 data-line-end=15 ><a id="Reproduction_14"></a>Reproduction</h2> <p class="has-line-data" data-line-start="15" data-line-end="16">Eagles are generally monogamous and form long-term pair bonds. They engage in remarkable courtship displays, including aerial acrobatics. Nest building is a significant part of their reproductive behavior, with some species like the Bald Eagle building massive nests that are used and expanded upon over several years. The female typically lays two to three eggs, and both parents share responsibilities of incubation and feeding the chicks.</p> <h2 class="code-line" data-line-start=17 data-line-end=18 ><a id="Pop_Culture_and_References_17"></a>Pop Culture and References</h2> <p class="has-line-data" data-line-start="18" data-line-end="19">Eagles have a profound presence in pop culture and literature, symbolizing freedom, strength, and nobility. They appear in countless flags, crests, and military insignias. In J.R.R. Tolkien’s “The Lord of the Rings,” eagles are depicted as noble creatures that come to the aid of the protagonists in crucial moments. In music, the rock band Eagles has had a lasting impact with their timeless songs.</p> <h2 class="code-line" data-line-start=20 data-line-end=21 ><a id="Conservation_Status_20"></a>Conservation Status</h2> <p class="has-line-data" data-line-start="21" data-line-end="22">Many eagle species have faced threats due to habitat loss, hunting, and poisoning. The Bald Eagle, once endangered due to DDT pesticide use, has made a remarkable recovery following conservation efforts. However, some species like the Philippine Eagle are critically endangered, requiring ongoing conservation measures to ensure their survival.</p> <h2 class="code-line" data-line-start=23 data-line-end=24 ><a id="Conclusion_23"></a>Conclusion</h2> <p class="has-line-data" data-line-start="24" data-line-end="25">Eagles, with their awe-inspiring presence and significant ecological and cultural roles, are more than just birds; they are symbols of the enduring spirit of the natural world. Their continued existence is a reminder of the delicate balance of ecosystems and the importance of conservation efforts to preserve these magnificent creatures for future generations.</p>','https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1497119146420-012f8fc80a3a?w=800&auto=format&fit=crop&q=60&ixlib=rb-4.0.3&ixid=M3wxMjA3fDB8MHxzZWFyY2h8N3x8ZWFnbGV8ZW58MHx8MHx8fDA%3D'),
